benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve bundle audit logs with history by id

covered: Valid Request: TC01 verifies successful retrieval (200) and schema/Content-Type for a valid UUID bundleId.
Empty Response: TC02 checks the endpoint returns an empty JSON array when no audit logs exist.
Not Found handling: TC03, TC15, TC16 cover 404 behaviour when bundle is absent or DB state varies.
Input validation: TC04, TC19, TC20 cover invalid UUID format, whitespace, and special characters for bundleId.
Authorization: TC05 and TC06 verify missing and invalid authentication scenarios (401).
HTTP method handling: TC21 verifies method-not-allowed (405) for non-GET.
Service error handling: TC07 covers service unavailability (503).
Edge cases & security: TC09 (UUID boundary), TC11 (SQL injection) cover input-edge and basic security validation.
Performance & scalability: TC10 (large dataset) and TC17 (50 concurrent requests) cover performance expectations.
Robustness & recovery: TC12 (transient network retry) and TC13 (regression malformed entries) cover resilience and data correctness recovery.
Integration & consistency: TC14 ensures consistency with other audit-log endpoints.
Tolerance for URL forms: TC18 (trailing slash) and TC08 (unexpected query parameter) verify benign URL/query variations are tolerated.
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination (limit/offset or paged responses) or behaviour when results are paginated.
Caching Behavior: No scenarios validate caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET behaviour.
Rate Limiting / Throttling: TC17 covers concurrent load but there are no tests for rate-limiting responses (e.g., 429) or throttle behaviour under rapid request bursts.
Authorization granularity: Tests cover missing/invalid tokens (401) but do not cover insufficient permissions/roles that should yield 403 responses.
Query parameter validation: Only an unexpected param is tested (TC08). There are no tests for supported optional query parameters, invalid query param values, or combinations of parameters.
Response headers and metadata: Aside from a Content-Type check in TC01/TC02, other important headers (Content-Length, caching, pagination headers, Retry-After on 503/429) are not validated.
Server error coverage: Aside from 503, there is no explicit test for 500 Internal Server Error or graceful error messages in case of backend failures (database, serialization).
Partial/streaming responses: No tests for partial responses, timeouts, or how very-large payloads are streamed/handled beyond a single response time assertion in TC10.
Rate-limit / retry semantics: No test for idempotency or client guidance when retrying after failures beyond TC12 transient retry.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: introduce scenarios that request different page sizes and offsets, verify link/header-based pagination (e.g., Link, X-Total-Count) and behaviour when requesting out-of-range pages.
Add caching/conditional GET tests: verify ETag and Last-Modified headers are present and that conditional requests (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since) return 304 when appropriate.
Add explicit rate-limiting tests: simulate rapid repeated requests to verify 429 responses and Retry-After header presence; include tests that ensure the system enforces configured quotas.
Add authorization-role/permission tests: include cases where a valid token lacks required permissions and assert 403 responses and error messaging.

Expand query-parameter coverage: if the endpoint supports sorting/filtering/other params, add positive and negative tests for those; if not supported, assert unknown params are ignored or cause expected responses consistently.
Validate response headers consistently: extend assertions to Content-Length, Cache-Control, ETag, Retry-After (where relevant), and any pagination headers across scenarios.
Add server-failure simulations: create tests that simulate backend failures (e.g., DB exception) to assert 500 responses don’t leak stack traces and return stable error payloads.
Add large-payload/streaming tests: beyond a single time threshold, verify memory/streaming behaviour with very large responses and how partial failures/timeouts are handled.
Clarify and enforce SLA thresholds: make performance assertions explicit (e.g., <2s) and add tolerance checks under concurrency/large payloads; automate these as part of CI performance tests.
